Weathering and the Formation of Soil

What is Soil?

  • Definition:
    Soil is the upper layer of Earthâs surface, composed of weathered minerals, organic matter, water, and air.
  • Importance:
    • Vital for sustaining plant growth.
    • Provides nutrients and a medium for ecosystems.

Soil Components

  • Minerals (~45%): Clay minerals, quartz, feldspar, and rock fragments.
  • Organic Matter (~5%): Decayed plant and animal material.
  • Air and Water (~50%): Fill the empty spaces between particles.

Soil texture

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Factors Influencing Soil Formation

  1. Climate:
    • Warm and moderate precipitation climates favor soil development.
    • Tropical climates can lead to nutrient-leached acidic soils.
    • Arid climates cause the accumulation of salts and limited organic matter.
  2. Parent Material:
    • Residual soil forms on bedrock.
    • Transported soil forms on unconsolidated material (e.g., river deposits).
    • Quartz-rich materials generate sandy soils; basaltic materials generate fertile soils.
  3. Slope/Topography:
    • Steep slopes limit soil retention.
    • Soil formation occurs where erosion rates are low.
  4. Time:
    • Soil takes thousands of years to develop.
    • Younger soils are found in recently glaciated or newly formed surfaces.
  5. Biological Activity
    • Organisms contribute to weathering and organic matter accumulation, enhancing soil fertility.

Soil and Weathering

  • Weatheringâs Role in Soil Formation:
    • Breaks down rocks into mineral particles and releases nutrients.
    • Mechanical weathering produces fragments, increasing surface area.
    • Chemical weathering transforms primary minerals into clays and dissolves ions.
  • Example:
    • In warm climates, chemical weathering dominates, leading to clay-rich soils.

Types of Soil

  1. Pedalfer Soil:
    • Found in humid regions.
    • Rich in aluminum and iron oxides.
    • Supports forest ecosystems.
    • The term â pedalfer â is derived from the prefix âpedâ (meaning soil) and âalferâ which refers to the presence of aluminum and iron oxides.
    • Typically reddish or yellowish due to iron oxides; the color can vary based on the specific mineral content and organic matter.
  2. Pedocal Soil:
    • Found in dry regions (Arid and semi-arid regions).
    • Rich in calcium carbonate (Water begins to move down through the soil layers, but before it gets very far, it begins to evaporate. Soluble minerals, like calcium carbonate, concentrate in a layer that marks the lowest place that water was able to reach. This layer is called caliche)
    • Associated with grassland vegetation.
  3. Laterite Soil:
    • Found in tropical regions (rainy every day).
    • Rich in iron and aluminum oxides.
    • Nutrient-poor due to leaching.

Soil Horizons

  • Definition:
    Soil horizons are distinct layers within a soil profile that develop over time due to weathering, organic activity, and leaching.
  • Importance:
    • Each horizon reflects specific soil-forming processes.
    • Understanding horizons is essential for agriculture, ecology, and environmental studies.

Soil Profile Overview

Source: https://iastate.pressbooks.pub

  • Typical soil profile includes six horizons:
    1. O Horizon
    2. A Horizon
    3. E Horizon
    4. B Horizon
    5. C Horizon
    6. R Horizon

O Horizon: Organic Layer

  • Definition:
    The uppermost layer composed of decomposed organic material such as leaves, twigs, and plant remains.
  • Features:
    • Dark in color due to high organic content.
    • Supports microbial and biological activity.
    • Found in forested or vegetative regions.

A Horizon: Topsoil

  • Definition:
    The mineral-rich layer mixed with organic matter, critical for plant growth.
  • Features:
    • Dark to brown color.
    • Contains nutrients, water, and microorganisms.
    • Known as the zone of leaching where minerals and nutrients start to move downward.

E Horizon: Eluviation Layer

  • Definition:
    A lighter-colored layer where leaching or eluviation removes minerals and organic matter.
  • Features:
    • Lacks nutrients and organic material.
    • Rich in resistant minerals like quartz.
    • Found in acidic or well-drained soils.

B Horizon: Subsoil

  • Definition:
    The layer where materials leached from above accumulate, also known as the zone of accumulation.
  • Features:
    • Reddish or brown due to iron and clay deposits.
    • Denser than the upper layers.
    • Stores minerals like iron, aluminum, and silicates.

C Horizon: Parent Material

  • Definition:
    A layer of partially weathered rock and minerals that serves as the source material for soil formation.
  • Features:
    • No organic matter.
    • Larger rock fragments are present.
    • Reflects the composition of the parent rock.

R Horizon: Bedrock

  • Definition:
    The solid, unweathered rock beneath all other soil layers.
  • Features:
    • Hard and compact.
    • Provides the foundation for the soil profile.
    • Weathering processes begin here to create the C Horizon.
